===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{cx|countable|sometimes|in the plural|lang=en}} The remains of a destroyed or dilapidated construction, such as a house or castle.
#* Addison
#*: The Veian and the Gabian towers shall fall, / And one promiscuous '''ruin''' cover all; / Nor, after length of years, a stone betray / The place where once the very '''ruins''' lay.
#* Buckminster
#*: The labour of a day will not build up a virtuous habit on the '''ruins''' of an old and vicious character.
#* {{quote-book|year=1963|author={{w|Margery Allingham}}
|title={{w|The China Governess}}
|chapter=Foreword|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2004261W
|passage=A canister of flour from the kitchen had been thrown at the looking-glass and lay like trampled snow over the remains of a decent blue suit with the lining ripped out which lay on top of the '''ruin''' of a plastic wardrobe.}}
# {{context|uncountable|lang=en}} The state of being a ruin, destroyed or decayed.
#: {{usex|The monastery has fallen into '''ruin'''.|lang=en}}
# {{context|uncountable|lang=en}} Something that leads to serious trouble or destruction.
#: {{usex|Gambling has been the '''ruin''' of many.|lang=en}}
#* Francis Bacon
#*: The errors of young men are the '''ruin''' of business.
# {{cx|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[fall]] or [[tumble]].
#* Chapman
#*: His '''ruin''' startled the other steeds.
# A change that destroys or defeats something; destruction; overthrow.
#: ''the '''ruin''' of a ship or an army; the '''ruin''' of a constitution or a government; the '''ruin''' of health or hopes''
#* Gray
#*: '''Ruin''' seize thee, ruthless king!

